{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496390"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1348"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1348"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.14,0.01,0.34,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110678"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92926"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43074"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110678"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of severe pain and swelling in his left first metatarsophalangeal joint. The pain and swelling were sudden in onset. He has been feeling fatigued recently, but attributes this to being \u0027hungover\u0027 from his birthday last Saturday night. He usually only drinks one to two cans of beer socially every fortnight but consumed around eight to 10 cans over that weekend as part of his birthday celebrations. He has a medical history of advanced chronic kidney disease secondary to vesico-ureteric reflux as a child. His medications include calcium carbonate and erythropoietin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The left first metatarsophalangeal joint is swollen, erythematous and exquisitely tender. Investigations reveal a creatinine of 450 \u03bcmol/L (60-110) with an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 12 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prednisolone","Indomethacin","Probenecid","Colchicine","Febuxostat"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute gout affecting the first metatarsophalangeal joint (podagra). The sudden onset of severe pain and swelling in this typical location, precipitated by alcohol excess in a patient with chronic kidney disease, strongly suggests gout rather than septic arthritis. The absence of fever and systemic symptoms, along with the patient appearing well, further supports this diagnosis. Advanced chronic kidney disease is a significant risk factor for gout due to reduced uric acid excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial therapy for this patient. Corticosteroids provide effective anti-inflammatory action for acute gout and are safe to use in patients with severe renal impairment. They can be given orally or as an intra-articular injection, with oral prednisolone typically dosed at 0.5 mg/kg daily for five to 10 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndomethacin\u003C/strong\u003E and other NSAIDs are contraindicated in advanced chronic kidney disease due to the risk of further renal deterioration and increased risk of gastrointestinal and cardiovascular adverse effects. NSAIDs can precipitate acute kidney injury in patients with pre-existing renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColchicine\u003C/strong\u003E, while effective for acute gout, requires significant dose reduction in severe renal impairment and carries an increased risk of toxicity, including gastrointestinal side effects and potentially life-threatening colchicine toxicity. The narrow therapeutic window makes it a less favourable choice in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFebuxostat\u003C/strong\u003E is a xanthine oxidase inhibitor used for long-term urate-lowering therapy to prevent future gout attacks. It is an alternative to allopurinol, particularly useful when allopurinol is contraindicated or not tolerated. While traditionally it was thought that urate-lowering therapy should not be started during an acute attack, current evidence shows that initiating or continuing urate-lowering therapy during an acute gout flare is safe when given with appropriate anti-inflammatory treatment. However, febuxostat alone without anti-inflammatory therapy would not be appropriate for treating the acute inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProbenecid\u003C/strong\u003E is a uricosuric agent that increases renal excretion of uric acid. It is ineffective in patients with an eGFR less than 30 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 and is therefore not suitable for this patient with advanced chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prednisolone is the treatment of choice for acute gout in patients with advanced chronic kidney disease.","NSAIDs and colchicine should be avoided in severe renal impairment due to increased risk of toxicity."],"references":["Hill EM, Sky K, Sit M, Collamer A, Higgs J. Does starting allopurinol prolong acute treated gout? A randomized clinical trial. J Clin Rheumatol. 2015; 21(3): 120-5.","Robinson PC, Stamp LK. The management of gout: Much has changed. Australian Family Physician. 2016; 45(5):299-302.","Gout [published 2024\u202fDec]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed 2\u202fAugust\u00a02025. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1348"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92926"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T20:24:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T20:24:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1348"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110678"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General 